  <h2 id="model"><span class="hash">#</span>Blinkit Selling Model (Pro Rata)</h2>
  <p>Blinkit operates on a Pro Rata model. As a seller, you contribute a per-SKU marketing investment and a per-unit fulfilment fee, while Blinkit takes a category-based commission on each sale. There are also daily storage charges that scale with how long your stock stays in the warehouse. Understanding this structure upfront is what lets you price each SKU correctly before launch, rather than discovering thin margins afterwards.</p>
  <p>The exact figures &mdash; the marketing investment per SKU, the fulfilment fee per unit, your commission slab, and the storage rates &mdash; depend on your product category, your pricing, and the terms agreed with Blinkit&rsquo;s Category Manager. Because these numbers change by category and are negotiated during onboarding, IARDO walks you through the complete, current figures for your specific SKUs during your consultation, so you plan with real numbers rather than rough estimates.</p>
  <p>To understand how Blinkit&rsquo;s overall fee structure works before you speak to us, see our guide on <a class="inline" href="https://iardo.in/blog/blinkit-commission-charges">Blinkit commission and charges</a>, or simply message IARDO for a personalised walkthrough.</p>

  <h2 id="roi"><span class="hash">#</span>Expected ROI on Blinkit</h2>
  <p>For brands that invest in marketing on a focused set of SKUs, the growth pattern is typically encouraging. The first purchase cycle usually generates a solid opening purchase order, and from the second month onwards, order values commonly grow as real sell-through data builds and Blinkit reorders based on genuine demand. Over the longer term, well-chosen products in fast-moving categories sustain visibility and repeat purchases.</p>
  <p>The specific numbers you can expect depend heavily on your category, your pricing, and how many SKUs you launch with, so a realistic projection is best done for your exact products. IARDO models your first-order and growth expectations during onboarding, based on comparable brands we have launched on Blinkit. Fast-moving consumer categories generally gain high visibility and traction once the initial marketing push lands &mdash; category fit matters more than almost anything else on quick commerce, and the right product in the right category compounds quickly.</p>

  <h2><span class="hash">#</span>Fulfilment &amp; Delivery on Blinkit</h2>
  <p>One of Blinkit&rsquo;s biggest advantages is its integrated quick-commerce infrastructure, which handles most of the operational load. The seller&rsquo;s job is largely to keep inventory flowing into the main warehouse &mdash; Blinkit takes it from there.</p>
  <div class="pick">
    <div class="opt">
      <h4>Seller Responsibilities</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Send inventory to the main warehouse</li>
        <li>Maintain stock availability and replenishment</li>
        <li>Coordinate dispatch and packaging compliance</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="opt alt">
      <h4>Blinkit Responsibilities</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Distribution from main warehouse to dark stores</li>
        <li>Final delivery to end customers</li>
        <li>Internal marketing campaigns and promotions</li>
        <li>Customer experience and last-mile management</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="pay-note"><span class="ic">&#128181;</span><span class="txt"><strong>Payment Cycle:</strong> Seller payments are generally released within <strong>15 days</strong> of successful sales.</span></div>

  <h2><span class="hash">#</span>Total Cost of Selling on Blinkit</h2>
  <p>Between marketing, fulfilment, commission, and storage, the true cost of selling on Blinkit is meaningful &mdash; and it should be factored into your pricing before you go live, not after. Pricing every SKU with the full cost in mind is what protects your margins from day one. Thin-margin SKUs are the ones that quietly lose money on a &ldquo;successful&rdquo; listing, so this step is worth doing carefully. IARDO helps you work out the complete cost for your specific products during onboarding, so every SKU is priced to stay profitable from the start.</p>

